snippet.title: AMBER HEARD POSTS A SEXY PHOTO ON SOCIAL MEDIA AMID TROPICAL VACATION
snippet.description:
Amber Heard Posts Instagram Picture Showing Off Backside In White Swimsuit The actress is taking a tropical vacation after launching herself in her film career and philanthropic causes.

Amber Heard was seen on vacation wearing a white bathing suit, showing her assets for a portrait taken and posted on her official Instagram. The film star added in the caption: "Sometimes a sign appears" in the photograph where she is seen hugging a palm tree with her hair in two French braids during her tropical vacation.

The Texas native is currently dating Heidi Klum's ex-boyfriend, Vito Schnabel, according to Us Weekly. He ended an intermittent relationship with Elon Musk in February 2018. Prior to his relationship with Musk, Heard was married to actor Johnny Depp from 2015-2017.

snippet.title: Amber Heard strolls bra less in Beverly Hills
snippet.description:
Eclectic chic! Amber Heard goes braless under black bodysuit as she shows off her unique style in Beverly Hills.
She slid into skintight green costume to play Aquaman's romantic interest Mera in this year's new Justice League film.

And though she was much more casually dressed, Amber Heard still wore an ensemble to catch the eye when she was photographed in Beverly Hills this Monday.



The 31-year-old, who earlier this year split from billionaire business mogul Elon Musk, seemed to have gone bra-less beneath a tight black top.

snippet.title: Johnny Depp and Amber Heard in marriage split
snippet.description:
Johnny Depp and Amber Heard in marriage split

Film star Johnny Depp and his actress wife Amber Heard are to divorce, US court documents have revealed. Heard, 30, filed for divorce in Los Angeles Superior Court citing irreconcilable differences.
They married 15 months ago and have no children.
They have recently been embroiled in a legal case in Australia after Heard brought two dogs into the country illegally. She pleaded guilty in April to a charge of falsifying documents.
Depp, 52, and Heard met while co-starring in the 2011 film The Rum Diary.
In the court papers, Texan-born Heard listed the separation date as Sunday.
Celebrity news website TMZ reported that Depp had asked a judge to reject Heard's claim for spousal support.
The split comes days after the death of Depp's mother. His latest film, Alice Through the Looking Glass, is due to be released on Friday.
The Australian court case started last year when Heard brought two dogs into the country where her husband was filming the latest movie in the Pirates of the Caribbean series.
When the case was settled, the couple released a video apology expressing remorse and advising travellers to respect Australian quarantine laws.
However, Australia's Deputy PM Barnaby Joyce had threatened to have the dogs put down, triggering a war of words with Depp that lasted for months.
The actor recently said on a US TV show that Mr Joyce looks "somehow inbred with a tomato".
Mr Joyce responded by saying he was "pulling strings" in Johnny Depp's head, like film villain Hannibal Lecter.

snippet.title: Charlize Theron, Amber Heard arrive to HFPA‚Äôs annual grants banquet, attendees are divided over Osca
snippet.description:
(10 Aug 2018) CHARLIZE THERON, AMBER HEARD ARRIVE TO HFPA'S ANNUAL GRANTS BANQUET, ATTENDEES ARE DIVIDED OVER OSCAR CHANGES
Lena Waithe is all for the new popular film category at the Oscars. 
The actress and Emmy-winning "Master of None" writer is thrilled that the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences is introducing an award for "outstanding achievement in popular film."
"I am all for it because a lot of those popular pictures have people in them that look like me and an Oscar is an Oscar is an Oscar. So people think it's so easy to win a popular Oscar? Do me a favor and go win one. But I think it's important. I think the Oscars have to change because the world is changing, people are changing. And Oscar day is like Christmas at my house. I have so many memories. I can still, you know, (remember) when Tom Hanks won the Oscar for 'Philadelphia.' He talked about the streets of heaven being lined with angels and 'act well the part and there the glory lies.' And Halle Berry winning the award and Whoopie Goldberg hosting that same night when they honored Sidney Poitier and Denzel Washington, all those things. It's an important show. It's sort of our Super Bowl. It represents us. So we have to make sure it's changing with the times because if we don't, then people will stop watching it and that will be horrible. So I'm here for the popular vote! Let's do it," she said. 
Waithe, who attended the Hollywood Foreign Press Association's annual grants banquet Thursday (9 AUG. 2018), was not surprised that Wednesday's announcement proved remarkably unpopular, at least among film critics and some academy members. 
"Look, I mean, the Oscars is an institution and it's like apple pie. So nobody wants to change the recipe for apple pie. But if changing the recipe makes it taste better, then let's do it. I'm here for it, man. I think it's important," Waithe said. 
The introduction of a "popular film" category, beginning with the upcoming Feb. 24 ceremony to be televised by ABC, did not sit well with some. 
"I'm not so happy about that honestly. I think it's a difficult thing for‚Ä¶ We are not the MTV Awards and I found it disappointing," said Tim Robbins, who's charity The Actors' Gang is supported by a grant from HFPA. 
While Christian Slater simply wasn't interested in the new category debate. 
"Look, I don't really think about it too much really. God bless them. They've got to try to figure it out and there's so many other things going on in the world right now that actually have value and meaning that I don't think about it," Slater said.
The other new changes were met with a mix of praise and grumbling, like the move to shrink the broadcast to three hours and remove some categories from the live telecast.
"Coming from a stage background, I just know how important all of that stuff is and how hard they work and I think that they deserve equal presentation," said Cynthia Erivo. "They earn their nomination just as much as everybody else has. So I don't know. I think that they deserve the same air time."
The HFPA, who puts on the Golden Globes, awards millions of dollars in grants to charities every year and celebrates their efforts work with an annual star-studded dinner. 
This year, one of the HFPA grants went to RAICES, an organization that helps families separated at the U.S. border. 
William H. Macy hosted the event. Amber Heard, Jennifer Garner and Charlize Theron were among the celebrity presenters.

snippet.localized.title: Charlize Theron, Amber Heard arrive to HFPA‚Äôs annual grants banquet, attendees are divided over Osca
snippet.localized.description:
(10 Aug 2018) CHARLIZE THERON, AMBER HEARD ARRIVE TO HFPA'S ANNUAL GRANTS BANQUET, ATTENDEES ARE DIVIDED OVER OSCAR CHANGES
Lena Waithe is all for the new popular film category at the Oscars. 
The actress and Emmy-winning "Master of None" writer is thrilled that the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences is introducing an award for "outstanding achievement in popular film."
"I am all for it because a lot of those popular pictures have people in them that look like me and an Oscar is an Oscar is an Oscar. So people think it's so easy to win a popular Oscar? Do me a favor and go win one. But I think it's important. I think the Oscars have to change because the world is changing, people are changing. And Oscar day is like Christmas at my house. I have so many memories. I can still, you know, (remember) when Tom Hanks won the Oscar for 'Philadelphia.' He talked about the streets of heaven being lined with angels and 'act well the part and there the glory lies.' And Halle Berry winning the award and Whoopie Goldberg hosting that same night when they honored Sidney Poitier and Denzel Washington, all those things. It's an important show. It's sort of our Super Bowl. It represents us. So we have to make sure it's changing with the times because if we don't, then people will stop watching it and that will be horrible. So I'm here for the popular vote! Let's do it," she said. 
Waithe, who attended the Hollywood Foreign Press Association's annual grants banquet Thursday (9 AUG. 2018), was not surprised that Wednesday's announcement proved remarkably unpopular, at least among film critics and some academy members. 
"Look, I mean, the Oscars is an institution and it's like apple pie. So nobody wants to change the recipe for apple pie. But if changing the recipe makes it taste better, then let's do it. I'm here for it, man. I think it's important," Waithe said. 
The introduction of a "popular film" category, beginning with the upcoming Feb. 24 ceremony to be televised by ABC, did not sit well with some. 
"I'm not so happy about that honestly. I think it's a difficult thing for‚Ä¶ We are not the MTV Awards and I found it disappointing," said Tim Robbins, who's charity The Actors' Gang is supported by a grant from HFPA. 
While Christian Slater simply wasn't interested in the new category debate. 
"Look, I don't really think about it too much really. God bless them. They've got to try to figure it out and there's so many other things going on in the world right now that actually have value and meaning that I don't think about it," Slater said.
The other new changes were met with a mix of praise and grumbling, like the move to shrink the broadcast to three hours and remove some categories from the live telecast.
"Coming from a stage background, I just know how important all of that stuff is and how hard they work and I think that they deserve equal presentation," said Cynthia Erivo. "They earn their nomination just as much as everybody else has. So I don't know. I think that they deserve the same air time."
The HFPA, who puts on the Golden Globes, awards millions of dollars in grants to charities every year and celebrates their efforts work with an annual star-studded dinner. 
This year, one of the HFPA grants went to RAICES, an organization that helps families separated at the U.S. border. 
William H. Macy hosted the event. Amber Heard, Jennifer Garner and Charlize Theron were among the celebrity presenters.

snippet.title: Amber Heard and girlfriend Bianca Butti head out of Los Angeles
snippet.description: Amber Heard and her girlfriend Bianca Butti decided to celebrate Valentine's Day by getting out of Los¬† Angeles.The 34-year-old actress and her 38-year-old cinematographer girlfriend were spotted at Los Angeles International Airport on Sunday afternoon.While their destination was unknown, the happy couple masked up as they headed into LAX with their luggage.   Heard was spotted wearing a long-sleeved black shirt with an elaborate necklace that fell across her chest.She also stayed safe amid the COVID-10 pandemic with a multi-colored face mask covering her mouth and nose.  She had her blonde hair up in a bun, and completed her look with a pair of black sunglasses, a black leather purse, another black bag, black pants and black boots, while carrying a black coat.  Butti stepped out with a brown sweater with a light brown cowboy hat and a black face mask keeping her safe from COVID-19.She was pulling two large roller bags into the terminal while wearing black pants with another bag slung over her shoulder.The happy couple were first spotted kissing during a trip to Palm Springs back in January 2020, just before the pandemic lockdown.¬†  While it's unclear how they met and started dating, Butti works as a director of photography, having worked on the TV series Love & Hip-Hop: Atlanta and movies such as Eyes On the Moon, An American in Texas and most recently Bedroom Story.She shot a film entitled The Uncanny, which is currently in post-production, along with Measure of Revenge starring Bella Thorne and Melissa Leo.¬†Heard has been keeping busy as well, playing Nadine Cross in the CBS All Access streaming service series The Stand, which just wrapped its first season.¬†  She'll next be seen returning as Mera in Zack Snyder's Justice League, a four-hour version of the 2017 theatrical film which debuts on HBO Max March 16.She is also attached to return as Mera in Aquaman 2 alongside Jason Momoa as the title character, though it's unclear when filming starts.Heard is also set to star in Run Away With Me, following an American in Paris falls for a model and the two become intertwined in the criminal underworld of the European modeling industry.
